Find the number of ordered triples $(x,y,z)$ of real numbers that satisfy
\begin{align*}
x + y - z &= 0, \\
xz - xy + yz &= 27, \\
xyz &= 54.
\end{align*}

gt_solution:
Note that the graphs of $y = x^2 + k$ and $x = y^2 + k$ are reflections of each other in the line $y = x,$ so if they are tangent to each other, then the point of tangency must lie on the line $y = x.$  Furthermore, both graphs will be tangent to the line $y = x.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

real func (real x) {
  return(x^2 + 1/4);
}

draw(graph(func,-2,2));
draw(reflect((0,0),(1,1))*graph(func,-2,2));
draw((-2,-2)--(4,4),dashed);

label("$y = x$", (4,4), NE);
label("$y = x^2 + k$", (2,4 + 1/4), N);
label("$x = y^2 + k$", (4 + 1/4,2), E);
[/asy]

This means that the quadratic $x^2 + k = x$ will have a double root.  We can arrange the equation to get
\[x^2 - x + k = 0.\]We want the discriminant of this quadratic to be 0, giving us $1 - 4k = 0,$ or $k = \boxed{\frac{1}{4}}.$

Let $\ell$ the directrix of the parabola.  Let $C$ and $D$ be the projections of $F$ and $B$ onto the directrix, respectively.  Any point on the parabola is equidistant to the focus and the parabola, so $VF = VC$ and $BF = BD.$

Let $x = VF = VC.$  Then $BD = 2x,$ so $BF = 2x.$  By Pythagoras on right triangle $BFV,$
\[BV = \sqrt{VF^2 + BF^2} = \sqrt{x^2 + 4x^2} = x \sqrt{5}.\]Then by the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABV,$
\[\cos \angle AVB = \frac{AV^2 + BV^2 - AB^2}{2 \cdot AV \cdot BV} = \frac{5x^2 + 5x^2 - 16x^2}{2 \cdot x \sqrt{5} \cdot x \sqrt{5}} = \boxed{-\frac{3}{5}}.\][asy]
unitsize(4 cm);

real func (real x) {
  return(x^2);
}

pair A, B, C, D, F, V;

A = (-1/2,1/4);
B = (1/2,1/4);
C = (0,-1/4);
D = (1/2,-1/4);
F = (0,1/4);
V = (0,0);

draw(graph(func,-0.8,0.8));
draw((-0.8,-1/4)--(0.8,-1/4),dashed);
draw(A--B--D);
draw(A--V--B);
draw(C--F);

label("$\ell$", (0.8,-1/4), E);

dot("$A$", A, SW);
dot("$B$", B, SE);
dot("$C$", C, S);
dot("$D$", D, S);
dot("$F$", F, N);
dot("$V$", V, SW);
[/asy]

Geometrically, $|z + 5 - 3i|$ is the distance between the complex numbers $z$ and $-5 + 3i$ in the complex plane, and $|z - 7 + 2i|$ is the distance between $z$ and $7 - 2i.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, Z;

A = (-5,3);
B = (7,-2);
Z = (6,6);

draw(A--B);
draw(A--Z--B);

dot("$-5 + 3i$", A, NW);
dot("$7 - 2i$", B, SE);
dot("$z$", Z, NE);
[/asy]

By the Triangle Inequality, the sum of the distances is minimized when $z$ lies on the line segment connecting the two complex numbers $-5 + 3i$ and $7- 2i,$ in which case the sum of the distances is simply $|(5 - 3i) - (-7 + 2i)| = |12 - 5i| = \boxed{13}.$

Circle $C_1$ has center $(10,0)$ and radius 6.  Let $A = (10,0).$  Circle $C_2$ has center $(-15,0)$ and radius 9.  Let $B = (-15,0).$

[asy]
unitsize(0.2 cm);

pair A, B, D, P, Q, R;

A = (10,0);
B = (-15,0);
D = (0,0);
P = intersectionpoint(Circle(A,6),arc((A + D)/2, abs(A - D)/2, 180, 360));
Q = intersectionpoint(Circle(B,9),arc((B + D)/2, abs(B - D)/2, 0, 180));
R = extension(B,Q,A,A + P - Q);

draw(Circle(A,6));
draw(Circle(B,9));
draw(P--Q);
draw((-26,0)--(18,0));
draw(B--R--A);
